","politics"],"notable_blurb":"U.S. Ambassador to Iraq 1963-67","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_C._Strong","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST065","institution_blurb":"Beloit College B.A. 1938. Member Sigma Pi fraternity. Addressed Beloit alumni April 1967, just after leaving Baghdad, as one of the last Americans out of Iraq."},{"institution_id":"INST064","institution_blurb":"University of Wisconsin-Madison — graduate study."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"He passed a three-day entrance exam in 1939","body":"Robert Campbell Strong passed the three-day competitive examination for the U.S. Foreign Service in 1939. His first posting was as vice consul in Prague, Czechoslovakia — the same year Germany occupied the country. He then moved to Durban, South Africa, and later Sofia, Bulgaria, before returning to Washington.","number":1},{"header":"He was America's man in Taipei in December","body":"In December 1949, just weeks after the Republic of China government retreated to Taiwan following Communist forces' victory on the mainland, Strong was named Chargé d'Affaires ad interim of the U.S. Embassy Office in Taipei. He monitored Nationalist activities, handled sensitive communications about possible U.S. military assistance, and relayed Washington's formal protests when ROC aircraft launched air raids on Shanghai. He was the face of American diplomacy to a government that had just lost a billion people.","number":2},{"header":"Kennedy sent him to Baghdad in 1963","body":"President Kennedy appointed Strong U.S. Ambassador to Iraq on May 13, 1963, just months after a Ba'athist coup had overthrown Prime Minister Qasim. Strong had written the State Department memorandum recommending recognition of the new regime. He navigated a second coup in November 1963, Kurdish insurgencies, and growing Iraqi alignment with the Soviet bloc.","number":3},{"header":"A year after he left Baghdad","body":"Robert Strong left Iraq in April 1967. On April 21, 1968 — one year and ten days later — his son Gridley Barstow Strong was killed by artillery, rocket, or mortar fire during the Battle of Khe Sanh in Vietnam. Gridley was 21 years old.","number":4}],"bio":{"display_name":"Ambassador Robert Campbell Strong","first_name":"Robert","last_name":"Strong","middle_name":"Campbell","title":"Ambassador","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"robert-strong-1915"},"X00157":{"id":"X00157","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":["extraordinary_longevity"],"sources":[{"short":"FindAGrave"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0894","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1999,"children_ids":["HD0901","HD3140","HD3141"],"date_year":1939,"date_month":9,"date_day":1,"location_city":"Westminster","location_country":"United Kingdom"}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1916,"month":11,"day":18,"city":"Peoria","county":"Peoria County","state":"Illinois"},"death":{"year":2014,"month":10,"day":14,"city":"Tucson","county":"Pima County","state":"Arizona"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM100"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"She married in Westminster, London in 1939","body":"Betty Jane Burton married Robert Campbell Strong on September 1, 1939, in Westminster, London — the week before Britain declared war on Germany. She accompanied him through Prague, South Africa, Bulgaria, China, Taiwan, Washington, and Baghdad over three decades of diplomatic postings. She outlived her son Gridley, killed in Vietnam in 1968, and her husband, who died in 1999.","number":1}],"cr